SH.ANM.ALLW.ZS-nutrition.def: Prevalence of anemia among women of reproductive age refers to the combined prevalence of both non-pregnant with haemoglobin levels below 12 g/dL and pregnant women with haemoglobin levels below 11 g/dL.
SH.ANM.ALLW.ZS-nutrition.name: Prevalence of anemia among women of reproductive age
SH.ANM.ALLW.ZS-nutrition.source: World Health Organization, Global Health Observatory Data Repository/World Health Statistics.

SH.ANM.CHLD.ZS-nutrition.def: Prevalence of anemia, children ages 6-59 months, is the percentage of children ages 6-59 months whose hemoglobin level is less than 110 grams per liter, adjusted for altitude.
SH.ANM.CHLD.ZS-nutrition.name: Prevalence of anemia among children
SH.ANM.CHLD.ZS-nutrition.source: World Health Organization, Global Health Observatory Data Repository/World Health Statistics.

SH.ANM.NPRG.ZS-nutrition.def: Prevalence of anemia, non-pregnant women, is the percentage of non-pregnant women whose hemoglobin level is less than 120 grams per liter at sea level.
SH.ANM.NPRG.ZS-nutrition.name: Prevalence of anemia among non-pregnant women
SH.ANM.NPRG.ZS-nutrition.source: World Health Organization, Global Health Observatory Data Repository/World Health Statistics.

SH.PRG.ANEM-nutrition.def: Prevalence of anemia, pregnant women, is the percentage of pregnant women whose hemoglobin level is less than 110 grams per liter at sea level.
SH.PRG.ANEM-nutrition.name: Prevalence of anemia among pregnant women
SH.PRG.ANEM-nutrition.source: World Health Organization, Global Health Observatory Data Repository/World Health Statistics.

SH.STA.BFED.ZS-nutrition.def: Exclusive breastfeeding refers to the percentage of children less than six months old who are fed breast milk alone (no other liquids) in the past 24 hours.
SH.STA.BFED.ZS-nutrition.name: Exclusive breastfeeding
SH.STA.BFED.ZS-nutrition.source: UNICEF, State of the World's Children, Childinfo, and Demographic and Health Surveys.

SH.STA.BRTW.ZS-nutrition.def: Low-birthweight babies are newborns weighing less than 2,500 grams, with the measurement taken within the first hour of life, before significant postnatal weight loss has occurred.
SH.STA.BRTW.ZS-nutrition.name: Low-birthweight babies

SH.STA.MALN.FE.ZS-nutrition.def: Prevalence of underweight, female, is the percentage of girls under age 5 whose weight for age is more than two standard deviations below the median for the international reference population ages 0-59 months. The data are based on the WHO's new child growth standards released in 2006.
SH.STA.MALN.FE.ZS-nutrition.name: Prevalence of underweight, weight for age
SH.STA.MALN.FE.ZS-nutrition.source: UNICEF, WHO, World Bank: Joint child malnutrition estimates (JME). Aggregation is based on UNICEF, WHO, and the World Bank harmonized dataset (adjusted, comparable data) and methodology.

SH.STA.MALN.MA.ZS-nutrition.def: Prevalence of underweight, male, is the percentage of boys under age 5 whose weight for age is more than two standard deviations below the median for the international reference population ages 0-59 months. The data are based on the WHO's new child growth standards released in 2006.
SH.STA.MALN.MA.ZS-nutrition.name: Prevalence of underweight, weight for age
SH.STA.MALN.MA.ZS-nutrition.source: UNICEF, WHO, World Bank: Joint child malnutrition estimates (JME). Aggregation is based on UNICEF, WHO, and the World Bank harmonized dataset (adjusted, comparable data) and methodology.

SH.STA.MALN.ZS-nutrition.def: Prevalence of underweight children is the percentage of children under age 5 whose weight for age is more than two standard deviations below the median for the international reference population ages 0-59 months. The data are based on the WHO's child growth standards released in 2006.
SH.STA.MALN.ZS-nutrition.name: Prevalence of underweight, weight for age
SH.STA.MALN.ZS-nutrition.source: UNICEF, WHO, World Bank: Joint child malnutrition estimates (JME). Aggregation is based on UNICEF, WHO, and the World Bank harmonized dataset (adjusted, comparable data) and methodology.

SH.STA.OWGH.FE.ZS-nutrition.def: Prevalence of overweight, female, is the percentage of girls under age 5 whose weight for height is more than two standard deviations above the median for the international reference population of the corresponding age as established by the WHO's new child growth standards released in 2006.
SH.STA.OWGH.FE.ZS-nutrition.name: Prevalence of overweight, weight for height
SH.STA.OWGH.FE.ZS-nutrition.source: UNICEF, WHO, World Bank: Joint child malnutrition estimates (JME). Aggregation is based on UNICEF, WHO, and the World Bank harmonized dataset (adjusted, comparable data) and methodology.

SH.STA.OWGH.MA.ZS-nutrition.def: Prevalence of overweight, male, is the percentage of boys under age 5 whose weight for height is more than two standard deviations above the median for the international reference population of the corresponding age as established by the WHO's new child growth standards released in 2006.
SH.STA.OWGH.MA.ZS-nutrition.name: Prevalence of overweight, weight for height
SH.STA.OWGH.MA.ZS-nutrition.source: UNICEF, WHO, World Bank: Joint child malnutrition estimates (JME). Aggregation is based on UNICEF, WHO, and the World Bank harmonized dataset (adjusted, comparable data) and methodology.

SH.STA.OWGH.ME.ZS-nutrition.def: Prevalence of overweight children is the percentage of children under age 5 whose weight for height is more than two standard deviations above the median for the international reference population of the corresponding age as established by the WHO's new child growth standards released in 2006.
SH.STA.OWGH.ME.ZS-nutrition.name: Prevalence of overweight
SH.STA.OWGH.ME.ZS-nutrition.source: UNICEF, WHO, World Bank: Joint child malnutrition estimates (JME).

SH.STA.OWGH.ZS-nutrition.def: Prevalence of overweight children is the percentage of children under age 5 whose weight for height is more than two standard deviations above the median for the international reference population of the corresponding age as established by the WHO's new child growth standards released in 2006.
SH.STA.OWGH.ZS-nutrition.name: Prevalence of overweight
SH.STA.OWGH.ZS-nutrition.source: UNICEF, WHO, World Bank: Joint child malnutrition estimates (JME). Aggregation is based on UNICEF, WHO, and the World Bank harmonized dataset (adjusted, comparable data) and methodology.

SH.STA.STNT.FE.ZS-nutrition.def: Prevalence of stunting, female, is the percentage of girls under age 5 whose height for age is more than two standard deviations below the median for the international reference population ages 0-59 months. For children up to two years old height is measured by recumbent length. For older children height is measured by stature while standing. The data are based on the WHO's new child growth standards released in 2006.
SH.STA.STNT.FE.ZS-nutrition.name: Prevalence of stunting, height for age
SH.STA.STNT.FE.ZS-nutrition.source: UNICEF, WHO, World Bank: Joint child malnutrition estimates (JME). Aggregation is based on UNICEF, WHO, and the World Bank harmonized dataset (adjusted, comparable data) and methodology.

SH.STA.STNT.MA.ZS-nutrition.def: Prevalence of stunting, male, is the percentage of boys under age 5 whose height for age is more than two standard deviations below the median for the international reference population ages 0-59 months. For children up to two years old height is measured by recumbent length. For older children height is measured by stature while standing. The data are based on the WHO's new child growth standards released in 2006.
SH.STA.STNT.MA.ZS-nutrition.name: Prevalence of stunting, height for age
SH.STA.STNT.MA.ZS-nutrition.source: UNICEF, WHO, World Bank: Joint child malnutrition estimates (JME). Aggregation is based on UNICEF, WHO, and the World Bank harmonized dataset (adjusted, comparable data) and methodology.

SH.STA.STNT.ME.ZS-nutrition.def: Prevalence of stunting is the percentage of children under age 5 whose height for age is more than two standard deviations below the median for the international reference population ages 0-59 months. The data are based on the WHO's new child growth standards released in 2006.
SH.STA.STNT.ME.ZS-nutrition.name: Prevalence of stunting
SH.STA.STNT.ME.ZS-nutrition.source: UNICEF, WHO, World Bank: Joint child malnutrition estimates (JME).

SH.STA.WAST.FE.ZS-nutrition.def: Prevalence of wasting, female, is the proportion of girls under age 5 whose weight for height is more than two standard deviations below the median for the international reference population ages 0-59.
SH.STA.WAST.FE.ZS-nutrition.name: Prevalence of wasting, weight for height
SH.STA.WAST.FE.ZS-nutrition.source: UNICEF, WHO, World Bank: Joint child malnutrition estimates (JME). Aggregation is based on UNICEF, WHO, and the World Bank harmonized dataset (adjusted, comparable data) and methodology.

SH.SVR.WAST.FE.ZS-nutrition.name: Prevalence of severe wasting, weight for height
SH.SVR.WAST.FE.ZS-nutrition.source: UNICEF, WHO, World Bank: Joint child malnutrition estimates (JME). Aggregation is based on UNICEF, WHO, and the World Bank harmonized dataset (adjusted, comparable data) and methodology.

SN.ITK.DEFC.ZS-nutrition.def: Population below minimum level of dietary energy consumption (also referred to as prevalence of undernourishment) shows the percentage of the population whose food intake is insufficient to meet dietary energy requirements continuously. Data showing as 5 may signify a prevalence of undernourishment below 5%.
SN.ITK.DEFC.ZS-nutrition.name: Prevalence of undernourishment

SN.ITK.SALT.ZS-nutrition.def: Percentage of households which have salt they used for cooking that tested positive (>0ppm) for presence of iodine.
SN.ITK.SALT.ZS-nutrition.name: Consumption of iodized salt
SN.ITK.SALT.ZS-nutrition.source: United Nations Children's Fund, Division of Data, Analysis, Planning and Monitoring (2019). UNICEF Global Databases on Iodized salt, New York, June 2019

SN.ITK.VITA.ZS-nutrition.def: Vitamin A supplementation refers to the percentage of children ages 6-59 months old who received at least two doses of vitamin A in the previous year.
SN.ITK.VITA.ZS-nutrition.name: Vitamin A supplementation coverage rate
SN.ITK.VITA.ZS-nutrition.source: United Nations Children's Fund, State of the World's Children.
